Obtaining the predicting locations

In order to obtain a continuous map of precipitation, we need to make punctual predictions in a dense grid of locations. In R there are different ways to define a grid. In this case, we are going to use the DEM’s raster object (‘ras’) above obtained to construct the grid of predicting locations. The collection of pixel mid points make a grid itself, so we just have to extract the mid points and their coordinates of every pixel.

First of all, in order to save computation, the spatial resolution of the raster object can be reduced. Thus, the number of points of the resulting grid will not be so large, and further computation reduced.

Finally, the grid of points will be clipped by the border of CV.

  1. Reducing the spatial resolution of the raster. Reduction factor=1/16.
ras <- aggregate(ras, fact=c(4,4), fun=mean)
str(ras)

Coordinate scaling

With the ‘gstat’ library it does not need to standardize the XY coordinates unlike the previously used library ‘geoR’ in the kriging model. So, we use the original units for the X and Y coordinates of both objects ‘dat’ and ‘loc’.

Reference coordinate system

Set the reference coordinate system for the object ‘dat’, making it equal to that in the object ‘loc’.

proj4string(dat) <- loc@proj4string@projargs

Initialization of the object ‘gstat’:

Recursive creation of the object ‘g’ containing the information for the co-kriging model. First, we define it with the information of the variable ‘spring’ and then with the information of the variable ‘ALTITUD’. The global tendency is specified by the parameter ‘form’ (form = spring ~ X*Y). If we do not use tendency in our model, the parameter ‘form’ must be set to ‘form = spring ~ 1’. The parameter ‘data’ speficies the actual data.

g <- gstat(NULL, form= spring ~ X*Y, locations= ~X+Y, data=dat@data)
g <- gstat(g, form= ALTITUD ~ X*Y, locations= ~X+Y, data=dat@data)
(g)
## data:
## var1 : formula = spring`~`X * Y ; data dim = 212 x 14
## var2 : formula = ALTITUD`~`X * Y ; data dim = 212 x 14
## ~X + Y

Empiric and analytic variogram of the first variable

Empiric variogram with tendency.

varig_1 <- variogram(spring ~ X*Y, locations= ~X+Y, data=dat@data)

plot(varig_1, pl=T, main="winter")

Fit an analytical function for the variogram.

fit_varig_1 <- fit.variogram(varig_1, model= vgm(200,"Sph",80000,20), fit.method= 6)
(fit_varig_1)
##   model    psill    range
## 1   Nug 134.1796      0.0
## 2   Sph 777.0510 112353.2
plot(varig_1, pl=T, model=fit_varig_1, main="spring")

Empiric and analytic variogram of the second variable

Empiric variogram with tendency.

varig_2 <- variogram(ALTITUD ~ X*Y, locations= ~X+Y, data=dat@data)

plot(varig_2, pl=T, main="altitud")

Fit an analytical function for the variogram.

fit_varig_2 <- fit.variogram(varig_2, model= vgm(60000,"Gau",50000,5000),fit.sills = TRUE, fit.ranges = TRUE, fit.method = 7, debug.level = 1, warn.if.neg = TRUE, fit.kappa = FALSE)
(fit_varig_2)
##   model     psill    range
## 1   Nug  7195.274     0.00
## 2   Gau 61185.589 37469.85
plot(varig_2, pl=T, model=fit_varig_2, main="altitud")

Cross variogram

Joint specification of both individual and cross variograms by using the same variogram model for both.

g <- gstat(g, id= "spring", model= fit_varig_2 , fill.all= T)
(g)

Cross variogram

varig.cross <- variogram(g)

Fit an analytical function for both individual and cross variograms.

g <- fit.lmc(varig.cross, g, fit.method = 7, fit.ranges = FALSE, fit.lmc = TRUE, correct.diagonal = 0.90)

plot(variogram(g), model= g$model)

Co-krigin prediction

we need to have the same names for variables in both objects ‘dat’ and ‘loc’.

loc@data$ALTITUD <- loc@data$mde_100 
loc@data$X <- loc@coords[,1]
loc@data$Y <- loc@coords[,2]

Co-kriging function

kc <- predict(g, newdata=loc@data)
## Linear Model of Coregionalization found. Good.
## [using universal cokriging]

Map of co-kriging prediction:

par(mfrow=c(1,2))

# Predictions

loc1 <- loc
loc1$predict <- SpatialPixelsDataFrame(loc@coords, data=as.data.frame(loc@data$predict))
q5 <- quantile(loc1$predict@data[,1], c(0,0.10,0.25,0.40,0.60,0.75,0.90,1))
image(loc1$predict, col=brewer.pal(7,"BrBG")[7:1], asp=1, breaks=q5)

# Legend

br5 <- cut(loc1$predict@data[,1], breaks=q5, include.lowest=TRUE)
legend("bottomleft", legend=levels(br5)[7:1], fill=brewer.pal(7,"BrBG")[1:7], title= "predictions", cex=1)

# Observed data

q6 <- quantile(dat@data$spring, c(0,0.10,0.25,0.40,0.60,0.75,0.90,1))
br6 <- cut(dat@data$spring, breaks=q6, include.lowest=TRUE)
points(dat@coords[,1], dat@coords[,2], col=brewer.pal(7,"Spectral")[7:1][br6], asp=1, pch=16)
legend("bottomright", legend=levels(br6)[7:1], fill=brewer.pal(7,"Spectral")[1:7], title= "observations", cex=1)

# Predicting errors

loc1$predict.sd <- SpatialPixelsDataFrame(loc@coords, data=as.data.frame(loc@data$predict.sd))
q7 <- quantile(loc1$predict.sd@data[,1], c(0,0.10,0.25,0.40,0.60,0.75,0.90,1))
image(loc1$predict.sd, col=brewer.pal(7,"BrBG")[7:1], asp=1, breaks=q7)

# Legend

br7 <- cut(loc1$predict.sd@data[,1], breaks=q7, include.lowest=TRUE)
legend("bottomright", legend=paste(levels(br7)[7:1],c("q0.10","q0.25","q0.40","q0.60","q0.75","q0.90","q1.0")[7:1]), fill=brewer.pal(7,"BrBG")[1:7], title= "predictions", cex=1)

# Observed points

points(dat@coords[,1], dat@coords[,2], col=brewer.pal(7,"Spectral")[7:1][br6], asp=1, pch=16)
